There were many calls to the helpdesk to fix other issues. The one I was glad to have an EEOC POC was my computer name. The IT helpdesk refused to change it, even after I explained I'm a developer I see it everyday. Luckily EEOC stepped in and explained why it needed done. It(13)

It was about bathrooms, and how to inform my coworkers. For the bathroom, we agreed a full email to every one on my floor, 100+ people, some companies I don't even work with, to inform them that I was changing my name, gender and using the woman's bathroom and where to send (10)

Then, the complicated part, which IMO could have been handled much better. I had to setup a meeting with EEOC, the client agency and my company. The meeting was with the VP of the EEOC division, client agency HR contact, my company's HR contact, my project lead, and manager. (9)

I wanted to come out at work immediately but this was before Thanksgiving break, so was asked if I could wait until after the new year to break the news to the rest of my coworkers. Meanwhile, I talked to my companies HR, to see what I needed to do to get everything changed. (8)

as a contractor and her an employee. She was very happy and very supportive. I must have asked her a thousand questions. But after my personal non-business meeting, I talked to my supervisor and manager. I got overwhelming support surprisingly, again not what I expected. (7)

right away but she eventually came around, so it wasn't what I expected. I also came out to my cis male roommate, sister and cousin. All of them supported me fully, so it gave me the confidence to come out at work. I first talked to "N", well I had to get permission first (6)

not ready at the time. A year later, I decided I couldn't live like this anymore, I spent about 15 years in the closet knowing I was a trans girl but to afraid to take the first step. I needed to do something. So I came out in Halloween 2018 to my mother. She didnt support me (5)

I was surprised to say the least. I really thought I was the only trans person in the closet in that whole agency. No one came out before. I watched as my coworkers deadnamed/misgendered her for months. I wanted to offer my support but was scared I would out myself and I was (4)

I gave up hope for family, friends or work to accept me as a girl. So my ultimate plan was to cut myself off from absolutely everyone in my life, start over and transition. But then "N" came out as a trans, and an email was sent out with her updated name and training slides. (3)

I will refer to her as "N", from now on. This was three years ago, I was hesitant of coming out at work, in fact I was not planning to do so at all. Me coming out was supposed to be me resigning. I wanted to move to California to transition. It was my long term goal but (2)

@VivaViverz That is reassuring, I am going still push for stimulant next week but it makes me feel better. Yes, I struggle with keeping track of time. Somehow I missed an "all hands" meeting yesterday thinking it was today. I also burn food whenever I forget to set a timer, which is often.

Lastly I know ADHD is different for everyone. I am only sharing my experiences. I believe that how someone treats ADHD is a personal choice, no one size fits all. For myself, I am hoping medication will help me control my worse symptoms and allow me to not struggle and do my job.

This whole thing has got me frustrated. I sometimes wish I never figured out I had ADHD. But it would have probably have still sucked. I would still be at -72 hours and I would have no way to explain how I burned through 200+ hours of leave without going on a single vacation. (7)

Next week is my follow up. I hope to try to convince my psych that the current medication is not working for me and want to try a stimulant. This might be difficult because of my chronic chest pains. But I am hoping we can do a trial run to see if my symptoms are better.(6)

It dropped to -60 hours back in October and I switched to part time (30 hrs). This is when I realized, I needed a doctor's diagnosis. I found a pyschiatrist who diagnoses adults with ADHD and I was officially diagnosed with inattentive ADHD 3 wks ago and prescribed medication.(5)

I did not even notice this until my leave balance went from 120 hours to below zero about 9 months ago. This is when I realized I might have ADHD but did not actively pursue a diagnosis or want more medication. But despite my best efforts my leave continued to drop. (4)

I remember being one of the first people in the office and the last to leave, I should have had more than that. But my timesheet and negative leave balance said otherwise. I was masking I was struggling then. Only my leave told the truth. Not one of my managers noticed this. (3)

Everyone told me my procrastination was due to a bad habit and could be broken. I actually thought I was doing okay until I looked at my timesheet. I was working 35 hours per week, instead of the normal 40 hours, since at least 2016. This did not make sense. (2)

Tbh, this week has not been a good week for me. My ADHD symptoms are kicking my ass despite my current medication. I logged 12 hours of work this week which is a record low for me. 9 months ago I did not know I had ADHD, I thought my tendency to procrastinate was typical. 🧵(1/8)

I think he finally accepted me as "Sabrina" but he has yet to call me sister. I have been trying to leave hints by saying brother a lot, but he seems oblivious. We have not talked much since I transitioned and never about how he felt about it. It hurts because we were so close.

Transitioning allowed me to get closer to my sister but further from my brother. Last year though despite not seeing him, my brother did send me a gift card in the mail and he wrote my name three times on the envelopes and card, I was touched. I loved it so much.

During my third year of college, I moved out of my mother's house, so this was the last time I saw both siblings daily. Then I graduated and moved out of state which meant I saw them 1-2 times a year. Then when I transitioned, my brother did not speak to me during those visits.

He was closer to our father, I was closer to our mother, my sister was in between. There was a lot of tension there, because I refused to visit my father growing up because of the way he treated me. My excuse was that I was working all the time, which was a loophole in custody.

Today is my little brother's birthday. Ironically he was born almost exactly 2 years after me, so our birthdays were celebrated together growing up. We used to be close as "brothers", but as we got older we drifted apart. Then my parents divorce estranged us even more.

So I think it was the combo of everything that year which led me to come out, buying yoga pants, exploring my gender identity with femme clothing, positive trans chars, and inspiration from trans people in my life. Then a mostly positive coming out allowed me to transition. (20)

I don't see her as much anymore since moving to CA but I believe she gave me the courage to come out. TV series, like Sense 8 and Orange is the New Black and Supergirl, also helped me discover myself more. I saw positive representation of trans characters I could relate to. (19)

A year before I came out, another trans woman at my work came out. I think she inspired me a little. By knowing that she was mostly accepted by her peers gave me a sense of how my coming out would go. We connected and had lunch after I came out and I think I helped her too. (18)

So why did I wait so long, why did I explore the idea of being a crossdresser for a few months. I think it was because I didn't know any other trans person in real life and media representation of trans people were awful. I was also terrified of coming out then. (17)

But then again transitioning was not an accident. I was planning on transitioning for years. I grew my hair out years in advance before I came out. I realized I wanted GRS at 16. I knew I wanted hormones before that at 15. I dreamed and wished I was a girl as early as 7. (16)

I would like to think I wouldn't have been. It's hard to know for sure though, I was in the closet for 15 years. In that timeframe I questioned over and over again if I was trans. I actually didn't really experience dysphoria until I started transitioning. (15)

So what started as buying yoga pants, quickly escalated to nightly crossdressing and later progressed to me starting HRT and transitioning months later. It's another one of those moments of what if I didn't buy those yoga pants, would I have still been in the closet today. (14)

That next month, I came out as trans, at first to my mother on Halloween and then in November to my family. When I came out to my roommate he was not surprised. Apparently he saw me a few times in my lingerie and wearing nail polish on my toes after that package incident. (13)

The package was all lingerie, panties, bras, slips, babydolls, night gowns, etc. I expanded my shopping after that. I bought a electric leg razor, a flat iron, jewelry, my silk bed sheets, dozens of t-shirts, my three pride flags, and lots of different colored nail polishes. (12)

My roommate picked it up and he approached me and said that he thinks there was a package that was accidentally delivered to our mailbox. I was like no, I ordered that and said I got a little carried away ordering yoga clothing. He bought my lie or so it seemed. (11)

What I didn't have was women's underwear, bras, and other lingerie, so I ordered from Victoria's Secret. For some odd reason I thought VS was discreet with their shipping, I was so wrong. The package arrived in a black bag with large bright pink letters of the company name. (10)

By September, a few months after I started this journey, I realized I didn't want to just wear women's clothing and be a crossdresser, I wanted to be a girl all the time and transition. By then I had accumulated skirts, dresses, sweaters, pants, wigs, breast forms, etc. (9)

I loved all my purchases of yoga pants so I expanded to women's t-shirts. Then weeks later I expanded to all women's clothing including lingerie. But I had a male roommate, so at first I ordered all my women's clothing from crossdressing and sissy femme sites. (8)

I was sad but ordering from that company gave me an idea, switch the gender of clothing on my search bar when shopping at online stores. I knew my size in women's, so this was easy for me. The results were much better. I went on a few shopping sprees at various yoga stores. (7)

I also really loved both yoga pants as well, they fit me perfectly. I decided to order more this time but not be restricted by gender. I added two more I really wanted earlier, both women's. Unfortunately they were sold out and the company went out of business. (6)

It basically said dear Miss "deadname", we are so happy you chose our business, please find a free pair of yoga pants for our gratitude and hope you order with us again soon. I was euphoric, this was the first time anyone called me "Miss" and I really loved it. (5)

This was actually the first item of women's clothing I ever ordered in my life. The site I ordered from was so happy for me being a customer they surprisingly shipped me another pair of yoga pants for free with a thank you card. I really wish I kept that card. (4)

So I searched for tie dye and found what I was looking for on a site of a small business located ironically in California. The search results led me to the men's section but they were sold out. I was disappointed, but I really wanted these, so I decided to order women's. (3)

I knew I was trans since I was a child about 15, but I did not come out until 15 years later. The defining moment that triggered me coming out was 5 months prior in May 2018. I wanted to buy yoga pants but didn't want the plain solid color ones I was seeing in online stores. (2)

I see this question get asked a lot "what was the defining moment of your transition". I usually respond with a short answer that was when I first wore women's yoga pants, but the real answer is much more complicated, so here is one of my long threads. 🧵 (1/20)

I run through these types of questions in my head a lot. There are so many points in my life I could have come out but I didn't and all I can think is that is was not the right time. What I keep telling myself is that I transitioned at the best time I possibly could have. (10)

Despite all that, I been thinking about it lately. What if I did come out then? Would my team then supported me? Would the guys have treated me differently and objectify me? Would I have been accepted by the girls? How different would be my life, would have I even graduated? (9)

The next work day it was mostly forgotten. I think all the guys were to drunk to remember that night. I remembered and decided not to come out then. I still got compared to that girl frequently though, what surprised me is that my boss compared me to her during my reviews. (8)

The one guy said that we would support you if you decided to transition. I was so close to coming out but instead said no again. The others told me they would be here for me if I changed my mind. But one guy still saw this as a joke, and teased me about it relentlessly. (7)

Then they all started laughing, I didn't realize the statement was a joke. I think they picked up on that fact and asked if I was trans and actually considering transitioning. I tried to cover up and responded with no. Some picked up I was uncomfortable and tried to reassure. (6)

They said I was the most feminine in the group and would look very hot as a girl. I didn't know how to respond, I desperately wanted to transition but what the guys said earlier made me extremely uncomfortable. So, I said no but apparently not very convincingly. (5)

The conversation shifted to how hot she was and they started to objectify her. Then they said they missed a girl in the group and said one of us should transition and take her place. Then they all stared at me. I was taken back and tried to ask why me. (4)

A few months after I started work the guys and I went to a bar for a happy hour. For some reason, I asked about the girl I replaced. I wanted to know what she was like and how receptive everybody was of her transitioning. I got supportive answers at first but it didn't last. (3)

I just got hired at a job on campus and I was hired to replace the girl that graduated the year before, ironically she was also trans. This is the first time I knew somebody in real life who was trans. My coworkers missed her presence but it came off a little creepy to me. (2)

Thinking about the time in college where I was told by a bunch of drunk guys at a happy hour that I should transition and "become" a girl. This was back in 2010, during my junior year at my university, I was 21 and it was 8 years before I came out and started HRT.🧵 (1/10)

Maybe I am toxic too and probably did not need to make a 25 tweet long thread bashing my parents, but it felt good to write all this down, a little therapeutic maybe. I will probably delete soon anyway, since I am no longer yelling into a void anymore with 2500+ followers.

In conclusion, I am happy my parents support my gender transition and don't misgender me but there is a big reason why I do not visit them often and moved further away each couple of years, including moving 2800 miles away from both of them to Southern California recently.

I actually did think of the pandemic back then. I asked my mother to make sure she got tested before visiting me and I was required to get a test 3 days prior to surgery. She didn't like the idea but I convinced her. But it didn't matter because she never took the trip. (25)

I say initially because weeks later, a few days before surgery he bailed and said he cannot do it. He was busy and did not have the time to drive my mother 200 miles and back. I gave up. I did not have anyone to take care of me that week. It was hardest week of my life. (24)

I did not think I could do this my recovery myself. She told me she could not, apparently she got lost from the last surgery and it made her upset with 4-5 lanes of traffic. She never been to a city before. But I kept begging so she asked my uncle and he initially said yes. (23)

This bounced my bank account as I only budgeted for one. So I drew the line there, no more of me buying her crafting supplies. Well my surgery was cancelled and COVID hit. When it was rescheduled months later I tried to get my mother to still drive down to take care of me. (22)

Months later she guilt tripped me into buying her a printer for crafting. Those machines are ridiculously expensive. It was supposed to be a one time deal to convince her to help me recover from my GCS. It turned into 3 expensive purchases, one the retailer double charged me.(21)

I cooled off by morning mostly. I hated she took advantage of me and then blamed me for not specifying a dollar amount. I never thought I had to, she would have never bought all that with her own money. But I still needed her to take care of me. (19)

About a year after I came out as trans, I started dressing up again. Another costume I always wanted to do is a witch. So that year I bought a sexy witch costume and wore it to a Halloween party and a less revealing version for work. I absolutely loved it and still have it. (12)

It wasn't until I was 11, that my brother and I went as Darth Vadar and Darth Maul. The last two years I went as the Devil, my mother gave up on us at that point. Apparently at 13 you are too old to Trick or Treat too. I didn't dress up for Halloween for another 17 years. (11)

I was heartbroken. I didn't know how to tell her I wanted to dress as a girl for more than just Halloween. I don't remember my costumes for the next four years. They weren't what I wanted. I wanted to be a witch, princess, fairy, and a mermaid and my mother kept saying no. (10)

When I got home I tried to convince my mother that next year I wanted to dress up as a "girl" cheerleader for Halloween. She was angry and said something transphobic along the lines of no "son" of mine will every dress as a girl even for Halloween. (9)

I was curious and asked them why they were dressed up like that and how did they get their parents permission. They told me they wanted to do this for a while but they convinced their parents it was a lost bet. I was intrigued and I think I met another trans girl that day. (8)

I was told by my mother that certain costumes were gendered for boys and girls, and I was a "boy". But here in my class was this "boy" dressed as a "girl" cheerleader. The "boy" had on a full cheerleader outfit (top and skirt) and a blonde wig wearing makeup. (7)

Back to my costumes. In 2nd grade I remember my brother and I dressed as power rangers. He was the blue and I was the red. I so wanted to be the pink, but my mother said no that is for girls. When, I got to school though that Halloween, I met someone who challenged her views. (6)

However, all the girls were complimenting my costume. My best friend at the time loved it, she thought it made me look really cute and her opinion was all that mattered. We were best friends since forever but drifted apart as we got older. (5)

I wore the whole costume probably 3 times. Once for school, my elementary school did a costume day for Halloween, and at least twice for Trick or Treating. When I got to school the boys made fun of me. I guess I was the only "boy" in a onesie with a tail wearing full makeup. (4)

I never understood her logic. I think she just didn't want to buy another costume. Anyway, I got excited when my mother showed me my makeup for the dalmatian costume. I got to makeup my entire face in white and have a few black spots and wear black eyeshadow. I loved it. (3)

My mother decided to go all out that year, it was before my sister was born, so it was just me and my brother in coordinating costumes. He was a kitten and I was a puppy. I actually wanted to be a cat too, but I remember my mother telling me I was too old. (2)

I love Halloween, it's my favorite holiday. I used to dress up a lot as a child. One of the earliest costumes was one my favorites too. I dressed up as a dalmatian at the age of 5. I was wearing this dalmatian onesie but my favorite part was the makeup. 🧵 (1/13)

They don't suggest I use the larger dilators though because of the micro tearing. They said it was like a few paper cuts and could heal on their own but be gentle. They also suggested I increase my dilating frequency to twice a day for a few weeks to see if that helps. (10)

As a longer term solution both nurses recommended that I should see a surgeon for another opinion. There unfortunately are none that specialize in vaginoplasty revisions in my area, so recommended LA or SF. In the meantime, they told me to use the lidocaine and take it easy. (9)

She showed the other nurse and they concluded I did have about an inch of granulated tissue in the far back and the tears could explain the bleeding, but other than that it looked normal and healthy. To address the pain, she prescribed me lidocaine as temporary solution. (8)

The difference around this time she used a light and went slightly deeper. She saw a liitle bit of granulated tissue in the very back. Then when she opened the speculum, she saw more of it. She also noticed a few micro tears but was able to get the speculum mostly open. (7)

She said the tissue looks healthy and pink but did not see any granulation that would explain my pain. She asked if it was okay with another nurse taking a look. I told her yes. When the new nurse arrived, she repeated the process the first nurse did. (6)

The sensation was similar to a dilator but different too. Once she got it fully in, she asked if I was pain. I was in a little but not more than dilating. She then proceeded to open the speculum slowly. At first it was fine but then I felt a very painful pinch and she stopped.(5)

She had me spread my legs wide and rest my feet in stirrups. Then using her fingers she prodded on the outside of my vulva and at the entrance of my vagina. Then she took a metal speculum and with lots of lube inserted it into my vagina. (4)

She then had me lay down and extend my arm above my head as she pushed and rubbed slightly with cream on each side. She said everything looks healthy and explained what she was doing so I can do it myself if wanted. Then she had me move forward for the vaginal exam. (3)

Once in the room, the nurse explained what she was going to do today, then asked me to get undressed and sit on the exam bed. She gave me two small pieces of disposable paper to cover up. Then she started the breast exam. She felt under my arm and then felt around each breast.(2)

CW/TW: Dilation, GRS, Blood, Vaginal/Breast exam

I got off topic here a bit, possibly twice, but my point is everybody on my team is doing so well and I am struggling with the "simplest" tasks, the same tasks I struggled with over 5 years ago. I wonder is it me? Was I ever a good developer? Am I making this harder for myself?

My current co-developer who I trained is also doing so well. I admired her immensely for being able to take over for me while I was out on disability for six weeks last year. She really stepped up in my role during then, I was so proud of her.

This was all before I came out as trans by the way. Since then he left the company and retired and I was perplexed how he could do that. He is only slightly older than me. I am happy for him but also jealous. I actually did love him and miss him so much, it's so confusing.

I always just thought my former roommate was much smarter than me. I loved him but he used to put me down a lot unintentionally telling me a task I struggled with was so easy and complained why it took me so long. I tried so many times to show him the task was much harder for me.

A few years ago, I was working with this older dev and he told me it was expected for his past team to work 50+ hours per week. This blew my mind, I would have never survived that type of project. My former roommate used to work 50+ hours too and I cannot fathom how he did it.

Lately I have been asking myself what is wrong with me? Why am I struggling to work the standard 40 hours per week? I looked at my timesheets, it made me more depressed. This has been an issue for me since at least 2017. I might never have worked 2 consecutive 40 hour weeks.

I might regret this but if it's what I got to do to keep my job and prevents my mental health from spiraling again, it's worth it. I know I should address my mental health problems too and I will. These plans will also allow me to go back to school again once things settle down.

I believe I can only get away with this budget for the remaining year. Next year it gets more complicated with federal student loans. Also, that new insurance deductible will complicate matters further with HRT and other healthcare. So glad I have no more surgeries planned.

It's not really because I am trans. It's just transitioning made me re-evalute my life and realize I do not enjoy or have the passion for programming or any type of IT work. I am more interested in biology and Bioengineering and want to go back to school for my masters in 2023.

Them: You have a college degree  and thinking about quitting your job and starting over in retail or food service, etc.

Me: Yes

Them: Why would you give up almost a six figure salary for minimum wage

Me: Because I hate programming and I am trans 🤷‍♀️
